args: Mom? Dad? Shion? Where are you?
Are you over here? Wh-what's happening?!
Ugh. That dream again. I've not had it for\nsome time. Perhaps it returns as the\ntime for the ritual grows nigh?
...Ah, look here. The portrait Shion\npainted of me. I'll not look at this\nagain, I wager.
The likeness? A sad one, at best.\nYet he put so much effort into it,\nI could not bear to discard it.
He really is a blessing of a brother.\nAnd so ADORABLE!
I, uh, brought that blood you wanted.\n...Bad time?

Ahem! Yes, well. My composure?
Momentarily lost. Might you be so good
as to never mention this to anyone?
Or erase it from thought altogether?
I certainly won't tell anyone, but I don't\nknow if I'll be able to unsee it.
It's clear that you love Shion very much—\nwhich makes how you treated him earlier\nall the more confusing.
You speak truth. My brother? Adored.\nWhich made my words from earlier\nall the more difficult to utter.
But it's best for both that I am no longer\nat his side. The sins I have committed\nare too great for his involvement.
I had hoped never to speak of this...
The deaths of our parents?\nMy offense. Mine alone.

I believe I spoke once before of how an
accident happened during the ritual to
pass this power from my parents to my
brother and claimed our parents' lives.
But alas, that is not the story entire—\nthe accident occurred only because\nof my own meddling.

I missed them on that day, and so set out
to see where the three of them had gone.
In doing so, I stumbled on the site where
the ritual was underway, interrupting it.
I remember little after that, save that when\nI awoke, it was to the sight of our parents'\ncold and lifeless bodies.
My brother was stricken. Grief-wracked.\nHis hands were clamped to my shoulders,\nshaking me as if to unseat the world.

And when I looked in a nearby mirror
and saw the symbol on my forehead?
I knew what I had done. The power—
Shion's by rights—was now mine alone.
So that's why you called it a curse.
Still, you shouldn't blame yourself.\nIt's not like you set out to harm anyone.
Intention is no matter. Thanks to me,\nShion cannot even recall the faces\nof our parents.
His life? His happiness? His joy?\nAll stolen by my hand.
The only way to atone is to give him\nsome modicum of happiness in return.
And the ritual is that way.

If the ritual is a success, the power that
has consumed our tribe's mana for so
long will finally be banished from this
world, along with my troubled soul.
My brother? He will finally be free.\nThis is my greatest and only desire.
Wait, hold on! You didn't tell me this\nritual involved you DYING!
I have serious doubts about that.\nYou two care so deeply for each other.
Delphi, I want you to reconsider this.\nI'm sure we can find a better way.
At the very least, sit down and talk to your\nbrother once more. Otherwise I'm not\ngiving you this dragonblood.
I'll find Shion and ensure he meets \nwith you. Just hold on until then.
I arranged for the two of them to meet,\nbut I don't know if it will do any good.\nDelphi seems to be in a bad way, and...
Do not struggle, Your Highness.\nThis is the Impenetrable Cage—it will\nwear off after a matter of hours.
I cannot do what you ask of me.

Even with the Shards, the life of a Tutelary
is a short one. No doubt that was why our
father tried to give his younger son his
power—to extend the life of the elder.
But they are dust now, and my end\napproaches with all speed.
It could be a year. Six months. Tomorrow.

Each day that passes will only serve
to remind my brother how few are left.
It is the height of cruelty, and I will
not stand to see him suffer so.
I have your dragonblood now.\nThe ritual can begin.
